{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512544"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:56:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:56:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11912"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11912"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0.23,0.59,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67882"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4508"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53347"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1564"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6647"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17000"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46077"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67882"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of persistent headache. She has a medical history of viral meningitis diagnosed by lumbar puncture six days ago, with a normal non-contrast head CT at that time. Her previous symptoms of neck pain, headache, and photophobia improved shortly after the lumbar puncture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe reports that this new headache is different, with no associated neck stiffness or photophobia. The headache is described as persistent occipital pain, notably aggravated by standing or sitting upright and relieved by lying down. She has been unable to attend work for the past week and is feeling very frustrated by her persistent symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has tried regular paracetamol and ibuprofen at home without improvement. In the emergency department, she is also given two doses of oral oxycodone with no change in her headache. She does not take any other regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management of this patient\u0027s headache?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV morphine","Repeat lumbar puncture","IV dexamethasone","Referral to an anaesthetist for consideration of an epidural blood patch","Sphenopalatine ganglion block"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this stem is most likely suffering from a \u003Cstrong\u003Epost-dural puncture headache (PDPH)\u003C/strong\u003E. This type of headache is thought to be caused by the removal of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) during lumbar puncture with continued leakage of CSF through the hole in the dura. The clinical features associated with this headache are that it is positional, aggravated by standing or sitting upright and relieved by lying down. It may be associated with nausea, photophobia, and neck stiffness. Risk of developing PDPH is increased with the use of larger gauge spinal needles, or where there have been multiple procedure attempts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of PDPH is typically based on severity and the patient\u0027s functional status. For mild cases, the first line of treatment is simple supportive measures such as rest, oral hydration and oral analgesia. Most cases will then resolve spontaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, this patient has already been using regular simple analgesia (paracetamol + NSAID) and also trialled oral opioid analgesia with no improvement. Not only has this headache now failed conservative management, but it is clearly impacting her function and activities of daily life (she has been unable to attend work), so further treatment is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidural blood patch\u003C/strong\u003E would be the next intervention to try. This would involve a referral to the acute pain service, and an anaesthetist would perform the procedure by injecting a sample of the patient\u0027s blood into the epidural space where the lumbar puncture occurred. The injected blood acts as a patch over the hole in the dura and reduces CSF loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect. Opioids have already been trialled in this case with no improvement, and there is no additional benefit to the use of \u003Cstrong\u003EIV morphine\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst steroids such as \u003Cstrong\u003EIV\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Edexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E might be used to treat a headache caused by increased intracranial pressure, the aetiology of PDHP is the opposite and there is no evidence to support the use of steroids in the treatment of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESphenopalatine ganglion blocks\u003C/strong\u003E have been proposed as an additional intervention for post-lumbar puncture headaches, however there is currently no evidence to support their routine use and an epidural blood patch would be the preferred intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no role for \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat lumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E in this case, as it is unlikely to yield new diagnostic information and will potentially exacerbate the headache through further CSF loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-lumbar puncture headache is positional, aggravated by standing or sitting upright and relieved by lying down.","When PDPH is refractory to conservative therapy and impairs activities of daily living, an EBP should be considered.","Risk reduction strategies for post-lumbar puncture headache include using non-cutting bevel needles, the smallest needle possible, and removing as little fluid as possible."],"references":["Uppal V, Russell R, Sondekoppam RV, Ansari J, Baber Z, Chen Y, DelPizzo K, Dirzu DS, Kalagara H, Kissoon NR, Kranz PG, Leffert L, Lim G, Lobo C, Lucas DN, Moka E, Rodriguez SE, Sehmbi H, Vallejo MC, Volk T, Narouze S. Evidence-based clinical practice guidelines on postdural puncture headache: a consensus report from a multisociety international working group. Reg Anesth Pain Med. 2024 Jul 8;49(7):471-501. doi: 10.1136/rapm-2023-104817. PMID: 37582578.","Patel R, Urits I, Orhurhu V, Orhurhu MS, Peck J, Ohuabunwa E, Sikorski A, Mehrabani A, Manchikanti L, Kaye AD, Kaye RJ, Helmstetter JA, Viswanath O. A Comprehensive Update on the Treatment and Management of Postdural Puncture Headache. Curr Pain Headache Rep. 2020 Apr 22;24(6):24. doi: 10.1007/s11916-020-00860-0. PMID: 32323013..","Schug SA, Palmer GM, Scott DA, et al. Acute Pain Management Scientific Evidence 5th edition. 2020. Available from https://www.anzca.edu.au/safety-advocacy/advocacy/college-publications"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53347"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11912"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53347"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T17: